We are seeking to hire a research scientist to conduct research projects in recombinant protein engineering, synthetic biology, molecular/cellular biology, and microbiology in the area of fuel and energy biotechnology. The position requires strong expertise and hands-on experience in bioengineering, synthetic biology, molecular/cellular biology, microbiology, research techniques and molecular/analytical instrumentation. This position intersects synthetic biology, microbiology and bioinformatics disciplines, and requires familiarity with identification and construction of biosynthetic pathways.

Minimum Qualifications:

M.S with 4 years of experience post-graduation or Ph.D. degree in bioengineering, biomolecular sciences, molecular biology, biochemistry, microbiology, or related fields. Key qualifications include experience with recombinant DNA techniques, cloning, genetic circuits and other synthetic biology strategies, BLS 2 microbiological techniques, bacterial and fungal cultivation, preparation of media, buffers and solutions, PCR, qPCR, cDNA, agarose electrophoresis, nucleic acids isolations, protein purification, SDS-PAGE and Western blot, ELISA, FPLC, microscopy, technical writing and presentations. A minimum of four years of molecular assay development and related experience is required. Due to the nature of this position U.S. Citizenship is required.



Demonstrated proficiency with microbiological and biomolecular techniques, such as recombinant protein engineering and expression, small molecules/peptides/protein purification and protein characterization. Experience with transformation and cultivation of non-model microorganisms such as environmental yeast and bacteria, and photosynthetic bacteria/algae. Previous research in molecular and environmental microbiology with use of bioreactors/fermenters for scaling up synthetic biology products and FPLC approaches. General understanding of next-generation DNA sequencing, and bioinformatics. Other beneficial skills include familiarity with genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics and metabolomics, and Liquid Chromatography Mass Spectrometry (LC-MS) platforms. Demonstrate high motivation, innovation, critical thinking, and capacity to work independently and collaboratively in a high-performance R&D laboratory environment. A record of R&D accomplishments that include peer-reviewed publications and other technical writings in molecular biology is preferred. Experience in bioengineering with process scale-up and purification optimization for biologics and biosynthetic molecules is a plus.

Are you interested in enabling end-users and data scientists access to the data they need when they need it? We’re hiring Big Data Engineers to morph an existing system built on top of ElasticSearch into a Data Hub. This system currently ingests data from multiple sources, normalizes that data into a common data model, provides full-text search across the entire collection, and allows access for downstream dissemination services. Through this re-architecture, we will expand the capabilities to provide a secure, highly available, and scalable environment for both humans and machines to derive the insights and analytics required to make mission-critical decisions. With your help, we will enrich the data with external AI/ML tools via event based processing, provide additional analytics and change detection services, and provide data scientists access to the data holdings to enhance our existing processes and tools.
We’re looking for Big Data Engineers with knowledge of various data access patterns and underlying technology implementations. You should be knowledgeable on how to properly secure the data from unauthorized access at multiple data access points (e.g. search discovery rules, repository read rules, S3 bucket policies, etc). You should also know how to keep distributed data stores in-sync and how to detect state drift. Finally, you should have excellent knowledge of the AWS ecosystem to support both the existing infrastructure (built on EC2 with CloudFormation) and to help us build the next-generation data hub.

Trileaf is seeking a full time entry level Project Scientist with 0 to 3 years of experience conducting National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA) / Section 106 Reports and/or environmental due diligence work (including Phase I Environmental Site Assessments) from our St. Louis, MO office.
The Section 106 / NEPA Scientist position’s main responsibility is the drafting and compilation of a standardized summary report. Maintaining expertise regarding the overall Section 106 / NEPA laws and the FCC’s interpretation of their application is a key element of the position. The National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA) and Section 106 of the National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA) requires federal agencies (such as the FCC) to assess the effects its actions may have on historic properties and the environment. On behalf of our telecommunications clients, we investigate potential impacts, initiate consultation, and help to resolve concerns. With regards to NEPA research, our scientsits perform a screening of listed and/or proposed threatened or endangered species, critical habitat, National Wetland Inventory Maps (NWI), Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) Flood Insurance Rate Maps (FIRM) etc. All work is done in accordance with FCC Rules Title 47 of the Code of Federal Regulations, Part 1, Subpart I, rule sections 1.1301 to 1.1319. Subsequent to these activities, a Project Scientist must be able to interpret the complied information and prepare a report.

Are you interested in enabling end-users and data scientists access to the data they need when they need it? We’re hiring Data Lake Engineers to morph an existing system built on top of ElasticSearch into a Data Hub. This system currently ingests data from multiple sources, normalizes that data into a common data model, provides full-text search across the entire collection, and allows access for downstream dissemination services. Through this re-architecture, we will expand the capabilities to provide a secure, highly available, and scalable environment for both humans and machines to derive the insights and analytics required to make mission-critical decisions. With your help, we will enrich the data with external AI/ML tools via event based processing, provide additional analytics and change detection services, and provide data scientists access to the data holdings to enhance our existing processes and tools.

You should also know how to keep distributed data stores in-sync and how to detect state drift. Finally, you should have excellent knowledge of the AWS ecosystem to support both the existing infrastructure (built on EC2 with CloudFormation) and to help us build the next-generation data hub.

About the Company
Talis aims to transform diagnostic testing by developing and commercializing innovative products that are designed to enable accurate, reliable, low cost and rapid molecular testing for infectious diseases and other conditions at the point-of-care. While timely diagnosis of infectious diseases is critically important to enable effective treatment, testing is primarily performed in centralized laboratories, which require samples to be shipped for processing, delaying the return of results by days. Point-of-care testing solves this problem by delivering the timely information necessary for clinical care.
We are developing the Talis One platform, a sample-to-answer, cloud-enabled molecular diagnostic platform that, once authorized, could be rapidly deployed to distributed diagnostic settings in the United States and around the world to diagnose infectious disease at the point-of-care. The Talis One platform comprises a compact instrument, single-use test cartridges and software, including a central cloud database, which work together and are designed to provide central laboratory levels of accuracy and be operated by an untrained user.

We are seeking a highly driven scientist with broad interest in protein kinases, to oversee, organize and coordinate the activities of multiple researchers in a dynamic, comprehensive, inter-disciplinary initiative at the Department of Structural Biology, St. Jude Children's Research Hospital.

The Blue Sky Initiative "Seeing the Invisible in Protein Kinases" is supported by $35 million in institutional funding (more information in the St. Jude Strategic Plan 2022–2027, pp 62–63).

The project will extend the ultra-high field NMR spectroscopy and biochemistry approaches developed recently by the Kalodimos lab (Science 370, eabc2754, 2020) to study the human kinome. This is a large-scale project that aims to detect and structurally characterize the distinct conformational states populated by kinases, and to dissect the mechanisms of allosteric regulation and those underpinning oncogenic and drug-resistance mutations. This strategy will be integrated with and complemented by data-science and computational approaches developed by the Babu lab (Nature 587, 650, 2020), to systematically characterize the conformational landscape of the human kinome.

About the Company
Talis aims to transform diagnostic testing by developing and commercializing innovative products that are designed to enable accurate, reliable, low cost and rapid molecular testing for infectious diseases and other conditions at the point-of-care. While timely diagnosis of infectious diseases is critically important to enable effective treatment, testing is primarily performed in centralized laboratories, which require samples to be shipped for processing, delaying the return of results by days. Point-of-care testing solves this problem by delivering the timely information necessary for clinical care.
We are developing the Talis One platform, a sample-to-answer, cloud-enabled molecular diagnostic platform that, once authorized, could be rapidly deployed to distributed diagnostic settings in the United States and around the world to diagnose infectious disease at the point-of-care. The Talis One platform comprises a compact instrument, single-use test cartridges and software, including a central cloud database, which work together and are designed to provide central laboratory levels of accuracy and be operated by an untrained user.

At Density, we build one of the most advanced people sensing systems in the world. The product and infrastructure is nuanced and one-of-a-kind. Building this product for scale has been an exercise in patience, creativity, remarkable engineering, laser physics, global logistics, and grit. The team is thoughtful, driven, and world-class.
We build systems that are real-time, accurate, and anonymous by design. Our systems help today’s largest companies understand how their buildings get used. We have counted hundreds of millions of people.
Counting people in “real-time” is unique and particularly hard to achieve. It allows a user to walk into a room, beneath our sensor, and see the room’s occupancy increment 700ms later.
Today alone, Density will ingest over 1m events. In the coming year, our sensor network is on track to grow ten-fold. The overall system load is exploding. Maintaining our low latency standards requires an increasingly thoughtful system.
We’re architecting infrastructure where annual, unscheduled downtime is measured in minutes. We’re building intelligent redundancies so missed events are an oddity. We’re constructing an exceptional engineering team to support always-on, intelligible analytics generated on the fly.
This role reports to our Director of Data Science & Engineering.
As a at Density, you will work on algorithms developed for applications deployed on state-of-the-art remote devices as well as our cloud platform. The data you will work with includes ToF depth data, point clouds from radar, and device parameters. Algorithms include computer vision segmentation identification, 3D point cloud surface analysis, and optimization algorithms for sensor tuning. Join a team of experienced data scientists as we expand what is possible.

We are seeking a highly driven scientist with broad interest in protein kinases, to oversee, organize and coordinate the activities of multiple researchers in a dynamic, comprehensive, inter-disciplinary initiative at the Department of Structural Biology, St. Jude Children's Research Hospital.

The Blue Sky Initiative "Seeing the Invisible in Protein Kinases" is supported by $35 million in institutional funding (more information in the St. Jude Strategic Plan 2022–2027, pp 62–63).

The project will extend the ultra-high field NMR spectroscopy and biochemistry approaches developed recently by the Kalodimos lab (Science 370, eabc2754, 2020) to study the human kinome. This is a large-scale project that aims to detect and structurally characterize the distinct conformational states populated by kinases, and to dissect the mechanisms of allosteric regulation and those underpinning oncogenic and drug-resistance mutations. This strategy will be integrated with and complemented by data-science and computational approaches developed by the Babu lab (Nature 587, 650, 2020), to systematically characterize the conformational landscape of the human kinome.

We are seeking a highly driven scientist with broad interest in protein kinases, to oversee, organize and coordinate the activities of multiple researchers in a dynamic, comprehensive, inter-disciplinary initiative at the Department of Structural Biology, St. Jude Children's Research Hospital.

The Blue Sky Initiative "Seeing the Invisible in Protein Kinases" is supported by $35 million in institutional funding (more information in the St. Jude Strategic Plan 2022–2027, pp 62–63).

The project will extend the ultra-high field NMR spectroscopy and biochemistry approaches developed recently by the Kalodimos lab (Science 370, eabc2754, 2020) to study the human kinome. This is a large-scale project that aims to detect and structurally characterize the distinct conformational states populated by kinases, and to dissect the mechanisms of allosteric regulation and those underpinning oncogenic and drug-resistance mutations. This strategy will be integrated with and complemented by data-science and computational approaches developed by the Babu lab (Nature 587, 650, 2020), to systematically characterize the conformational landscape of the human kinome.

Job Title: Principal Scientist Protein Kinases (Blue Sky Initiative)
Job Description:
We are seeking a highly driven scientist with broad interest in protein kinases, to oversee, organize and coordinate the activities of multiple researchers in a dynamic, comprehensive, inter-disciplinary initiative at the Department of Structural Biology, St. Jude Children's Research Hospital.

The Blue Sky Initiative "Seeing the Invisible in Protein Kinases" is supported by $35 million in institutional funding (more information in the St. Jude Strategic Plan 2022–2027, pp 62–63).

The project will extend the ultra-high field NMR spectroscopy and biochemistry approaches developed recently by the Kalodimos lab (Science 370, eabc2754, 2020) to study the human kinome. This is a large-scale project that aims to detect and structurally characterize the distinct conformational states populated by kinases, and to dissect the mechanisms of allosteric regulation and those underpinning oncogenic and drug-resistance mutations. This strategy will be integrated with and complemented by data-science and computational approaches developed by the Babu lab (Nature 587, 650, 2020), to systematically characterize the conformational landscape of the human kinome.

The Company
Polarean Imaging plc and its wholly owned subsidiary, Polarean, Inc. are revenue-generating, medical drug-device combination companies operating in the high-resolution medical imaging market. We develop equipment that enables existing MRI systems to achieve an improved level of pulmonary function imaging and specializes in the use of hyperpolarized Xenon gas (129 Xe) as an imaging agent to visualize ventilation. 129Xe gas is currently being studied for visualization of gas exchange regionally in the smallest airways of the lungs, the tissue barrier between the lung, and the bloodstream and in the pulmonary vasculature. Xenon gas exhibits solubility and signal properties that enable it to be imaged within other tissues and organs.
The Challenge and Opportunity
Polarean's technology provides a unique and sensitive way to monitor changes in lung structure and function; it is currently used in basic and clinical research to study lung physiology and to monitor the efficacy of new drugs. After the successful completion of two Phase III pivotal trials showing equivalence to the FDA-approved standard of 133Xe Scintigraphy, followed by a positive pre-NDA meeting, Polarean submitted an NDA (new drug application) to the FDA in October 2020. The first approval in the US for this drug/device combination diagnostic is anticipated for Q3 2021. The initial target indication is for the evaluation of pulmonary function and imaging of the lungs using magnetic resonance imaging (MRI). Though initially centered on ventilation imaging, we are planning a life cycle management program to follow with new claims for gas-exchange imaging, new therapeutic uses, expansion into pediatric patients, and are developing more streamlined, automated devices to fuel company growth over the next several years.

Position Title: Research Scientist

Who is Active Motif?
Active Motif, Inc. is a privately held global biotechnology company with the vision of bringing the field of epigenetics into personalized and precision medicine. The company has focused efforts on supplying innovative kits and reagents for epigenetics and nuclear function research and performs specialized epigenetics-based experiments for leading academic groups and pharmaceutical companies. It offers research kits, assays, and biocomputing systems that help researchers study the function, regulation, and interactions between genes, proteins, and metabolic pathways. Active Motif, headquartered in Carlsbad, CA, has offices in Europe, Japan, China and the United States, and is represented throughout the rest of the world by distributors. Recently it announced access to a pre-print publication associated with their COVID-19 efforts in China to isolate, develop, and deliver high-value fully human recombinant SARS-CoV-2 antibodies to the market. In addition, Active Motif North America has taken the lead on the scale-up, manufacturing, and commercialization of over 19 clones which have been demonstrated to show value in both diagnostic as well as therapeutic applications. "We are proud of the effort made by the many employees at Active Motif who have taken the extra effort required to provide access to these antibodies and it is a great feeling to know that we can assist in making an impact on this pandemic," noted Ted DeFrank, President and CEO of Active Motif.
